## Building a Typewriter Effect in Vue 3

**Mental model:** A state machine that grows then shrinks `slice(0, count)` of the current phrase. State: phrase index, character count, deleting flag. A timed step adjusts count by ±1 and flips phase at the ends. Render the slice plus a blinking cursor.

### Step 1 — Index, count, phase
```js
const phrase = ref(0);
const count = ref(0);
const deleting = ref(false);
```

### Step 2 — Recursive timeout step
```js
function step() {
  const full = phrases[phrase.value];
  const atFull = !deleting.value && count.value === full.length;
  const atEmpty = deleting.value && count.value === 0;
  const delay = atFull ? 1200 : deleting.value ? 50 : 100;
  timer = setTimeout(() => {
    if (atFull) deleting.value = true;
    else if (atEmpty) { deleting.value = false; phrase.value = (phrase.value + 1) % phrases.length; }
    else count.value += deleting.value ? -1 : 1;
    step();
  }, delay);
}
```

### Step 3 — Render the slice
```vue
<span>{{ phrases[phrase].slice(0, count) }}<span class="cursor">|</span></span>
```

### Step 4 — Lifecycle
```js
onMounted(step);
onUnmounted(() => clearTimeout(timer));
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Pause at full | Longer delay when `atFull`. |
| Phrase wrap | Modulo. |
| Cleanup | Clear the timeout on unmount. |

**Interview tip:** A self-scheduling `setTimeout` (rather than a fixed `setInterval`) lets each phase use its own delay — typing, deleting, and the pause at the end all differ, which a single interval can't express cleanly.

