## Building a Typewriter Effect in Angular

**Mental model:** A state machine that grows then shrinks the visible slice of the current phrase. Fields: phrase index, character count, deleting flag. A self-scheduling `setTimeout` adjusts the count and flips phase at the ends. Clear the timer in `ngOnDestroy`. Classic `NgModule` setup, no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them).

### Step 1 — Fields
```typescript
@Input() phrases: string[] = [];
phrase = 0;
count = 0;
deleting = false;
private timer: any = null;
```

### Step 2 — Self-scheduling step
```typescript
step(): void {
  const full = this.phrases[this.phrase];
  const atFull = !this.deleting && this.count === full.length;
  const atEmpty = this.deleting && this.count === 0;
  const delay = atFull ? 1200 : this.deleting ? 50 : 100;
  this.timer = setTimeout(() => {
    if (atFull) { this.deleting = true; }
    else if (atEmpty) { this.deleting = false; this.phrase = (this.phrase + 1) % this.phrases.length; }
    else { this.count += this.deleting ? -1 : 1; }
    this.step();
  }, delay);
}
```

### Step 3 — Render via a getter
```typescript
get text(): string { return this.phrases[this.phrase].slice(0, this.count); }
```

### Step 4 — Lifecycle
```typescript
ngOnInit(): void { this.step(); }
ngOnDestroy(): void { clearTimeout(this.timer); }
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Pause at full | Longer delay when `atFull`. |
| Phrase wrap | Modulo. |
| Cleanup | `ngOnDestroy` clears the timer. |

**Interview tip:** A self-scheduling `setTimeout` gives each phase its own delay (type/delete/pause) — cleaner than one `setInterval`; just remember to clear it in `ngOnDestroy`.

